      <abstract>
        <p>Al Trenk, who helps run family businesses that operate heliport in Manhattan continues to pay his employees, who are assisting with rescue effort following World Trade Center attack, but may have to lay off some workers or close business (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Al Trenk, who helps run the family businesses that operate the West 30th Street heliport, had flown by the twin towers in a blue helicopter nine minutes before the first plane hit 1 World Trade Center. It was harrowing, he said.</p>
        <p>Ten days after the attack, he is reeling for another reason. The government's order banning general aviation aircraft from a 25-mile no-fly zone around Kennedy International Airport. Commercial, military and law enforcement aircraft can take to the air, but Mr. Trenk said he is losing $20,000 a day.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Al Trenk, who helps run the family businesses that operate the West 30th Street heliport, had flown by the twin towers in a blue helicopter nine minutes before the first plane hit 1 World Trade Center. It was harrowing, he said.</p>
        <p>Ten days after the attack, he is reeling for another reason. The government's order banning general aviation aircraft from a 25-mile no-fly zone around Kennedy International Airport. Commercial, military and law enforcement aircraft can take to the air, but Mr. Trenk said he is losing $20,000 a day.</p>
        <p>''It's not a time you feel like complaining when you have seen all the stuff that has gone on around us,'' said Mr. Trenk, who helps run Air Pegasus and Liberty Helicopters, which is mainly known for its tours.  ''It is a tough time. It's very depressing.''</p>
        <p>A Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman, Arlene Salac, said the no-fly zone was in place to ensure the security and ease of rescue efforts. But Mr. Trenk -- who is paying his 150 employees to assist  the New York Police Department, New York State Police, the Army and F.B.I. helicopters landing at the heliport -- fears that without relief he will have to lay off workers or shutter some of his business. Federal officials said they do not expect the restrictions to be lifted any time soon.</p>
        <p>JAYSON BLAIR</p>
        <p>A NATION CHALLENGED: NOTEBOOKS</p>
